'''Tajikarao Shrine''' (手力雄神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Ogaki City|ja|大城市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Gifu Prefecture|ja|岐阜県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, in Keno Mori District. Unlike many {{ill|Tajikarao Shrines|ja|手力雄神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} enshrining {{ill|Ame-no-Tajikarao|ja|天手力雄命|1=Ame-no-Tajikarao|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, this shrine's deity is {{ill|Ama-no-Iwato-wake no Kami|ja|天石門別神|1=Ama-no-Iwato-wake no Kami|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. (The rationale is explained in the shrine's history.)
== deity == * {{ill|Ama-no-Iwato-wake no Kami|ja|天石門別神|1=Ama-no-Iwato-wake no Kami|qq=draft|qq=draft}}
== Historical Background == The shrine was originally established during the Chōhō 3rd year (1001) by Numaha Giemon no Jo Sadakatsu after driving out bandits who had been threatening travelers in the "Difficult Forest" (Nangi Mori). Initially located in Kurikiba, it was relocated multiple times due to fires and reconstruction efforts. The deity was later identified as {{ill|Ama-no-Iwato-wake no Kami|ja|天石門別神|1=Ama-no-Iwato-wake no Kami|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and the shrine underwent significant rebuilding in the Shōwa era.
== Subsidiary Shrines == * Wakamiya Hachiman (deity: {{ill|Emperor Nintoku|ja|仲徳天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) * Suijin Shrine (deity: {{ill|Mizuhanome|ja|蔓象女神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) * Mikuwasha Shrine (deity: {{ill|Toyouke-hime|ja|豐受女神|qq=draft}})
== Accessibility == * Accessible via bus stops on the local Mie-Kinki bus line.
